2016 LAPD Crime and Collision Data Set

Here is a quick plot of the 2016 Crime and Collision data provided by the City of Los Angeles. The dataset can be found at the address below.

https://data.lacity.org/A-Safe-City/LAPD-Crime-and-Collision-Raw-Data-for-2016/ttiz-7an8

We will load the following packages to create a plot of the locations of each incident.

library(tidyverse)
library(stringr)
library(ggmap)
library(reshape2)

Importing and Cleaning Data

Crime_Col <- read_csv("LAPD_Crime_and_Collision_Raw_Data_for_2016.csv")

Cleaning Data

In order to make the dataset easier to work with, we will take clean up the spaces in the column names first.

colnames(Crime_Col)
##  [1] "Date Rptd"    "DR. NO"       "DATE OCC"     "TIME OCC"    
##  [5] "AREA"         "AREA NAME"    "RD"           "Crm Cd"      
##  [9] "Crm Cd Desc"  "Status"       "Status Desc"  "LOCATION"    
## [13] "Cross Street" "Location 1"
cnames <- colnames(Crime_Col)
cnames <- str_replace_all(cnames, "[ ]", "_") #stringr package
colnames(Crime_Col) <- cnames
colnames(Crime_Col)
##  [1] "Date_Rptd"    "DR._NO"       "DATE_OCC"     "TIME_OCC"    
##  [5] "AREA"         "AREA_NAME"    "RD"           "Crm_Cd"      
##  [9] "Crm_Cd_Desc"  "Status"       "Status_Desc"  "LOCATION"    
## [13] "Cross_Street" "Location_1"

We are interested in plotting the locations of each incident, and in order to do that we will focus on the data in the “Location_1”" column.

head(Crime_Col$Location_1)
## [1] "(34.0055, -118.3138)" "(34.1829, -118.6059)" "(34.1994, -118.4662)"
## [4] "(34.1877, -118.4421)" "(34.1718, -118.4993)" "(34.0196, -118.3632)"

We see that this column has the longitude and latitude of the incidents, but we need to split these values into separate columns in order to create our plot.

coord <-colsplit(Crime_Col$Location_1, "," ,c("Lat", "Long")) #reshape2 pkg 
Crime_Col$Long<- as.numeric(str_replace_all(coord$Long,"[()]",""))
Crime_Col$Lat <- as.numeric(str_replace_all(coord$Lat,"[()]",""))

The two values are separated into two different columns in its own table and we added it back into the dataset.

Subsetting Data

Now we will subset our data and work with the columns we are currently interested in. First we utilize the dplyr package to select the columns, and then filter out any rows with missing coordinate data.

Crime_Col_Area <- Crime_Col %>%
    select_("Long","Lat","AREA_NAME")
Crime_Col_Area <- Crime_Col %>%
    filter(Long != 0)

Let’s Plot

First lets grab a map of LA to plot our coordinates.

LA <- get_map("Los Angeles", color = "bw", maptype = "roadmap") #getting LA map to plot our points
## Map from URL : http://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/staticmap?center=Los+Angeles&zoom=10&size=640x640&scale=2&maptype=roadmap&language=en-EN&sensor=false
## Information from URL : http://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json?address=Los%20Angeles&sensor=false
plot(LA)

Now we can lay our points over the map of LA we grabbed above.

LA_Crime_Area <-ggmap(LA) + 
    geom_point(data = Crime_Col_Area, alpha = 0.05,
               aes(x=Crime_Col_Area$Long, y = Crime_Col_Area$Lat, color = Crime_Col_Area$AREA_NAME)) +
    theme(axis.title.x = element_blank(), axis.title.y = element_blank()) +
    labs(color = "LAPD Division") +
    guides(colour = guide_legend(override.aes = list(alpha=1))) +
    ggtitle("2016 LAPD Crime and Collisions")

Here we have our plot of the available points of each incidient and colored by LAPD Division.
